  "text": "Although I am an experienced interviewer, and a teacher of interviewing skills, not everyone I interview chooses to open up to me in the way that Katherine did. One way of understanding elusive differences between different interview encounters, is in terms of an unconscious dimension of two-way communication. If I am correct that Katherine's repeated reference to not wanting to do harm to others was, in part, an unconscious communication addressed to me about the possibility that I might do her harm, then what happened during the first phase of the interview can be understood as a period in which she tested out her sense of my trustworthiness unconsciously. As I have already said, during the interview itself I did not consciously think about this meaning of her phrase and I did not say anything designed to assuage her concerns, for example by reassuring her that I meant her no harm or wouldn't do her any harm. However, the fact that my later interpretation of her words as an unconscious communication made sense to me in relation to the trajectory of the interview, suggests that at an unconscious level something did register. In [CITATION_1] terms, that \"something\" was unthought, but nevertheless \"known\".",
